{"type":"message","id":"f0ecbe76","parentId":"b3c809ff","timestamp":"2026-03-02T08:41:27.849Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the issue now. Looking at the lease.js file, I can see that most of the sheet updating code is commented out. It's only generating the agreement PDF and sending the email now. The regex patterns in the code are trying to match specific patterns.\n\nLooking at the regex patterns:\n1. For tenant name: `to ([a-z .'-]+?) from` - expects \"apartment ... to Zayan from ...\"\n2. For apartment: `apartment (.*?) to` or `apartment (.*?) from`\n3. For room: `Room (\\d+)`\n4. For dates: `from (.*?) to`\n5. For amount: `(?:amount|for)\\s*\\$?(\\d+)`\n\nThe user's string is:\n\"apartment 90 Washington 24M room 1 to zayan from 11/11/2026 to 12/12/2026. Zayan email is zayanyaseen99@gmail.com and contact is 1234567890\"\n\nLet me check what will be parsed:\n- tenantName: \"to ([a-z .'-]+?) from\" → should match \"zayan\"\n- apartment: \"apartment (.*?) to\" → should match \"90 Washington 24M room 1\"\n- room: \"Room (\\d+)\" → should match \"1\"\n- startDate: \"from (.*?) to\" → should match \"11/11/2026\"\n- endDate: looking for a second pattern that's specific to dates in the \"from DD/MM/YYYY to DD/MM/YYYY\" format\n- amount: \"(?:amount|for)\\s*\\$?(\\d+)\" → will NOT match because \"24M\" doesn't fit this pattern (needs the word \"amount\" or \"for\" before it, and \"M\" is not a digit)\n\nWait, the issue is that the amount pattern expects \"amount\" or \"for\" before the number. The user said \"24M\" which doesn't match.\n\n\nI'll modify the regex to capture \"24M\" by making the unit optional and allowing multiple digits. The updated regex should look like `(?:amount|for)?\\s*\\$?(\\d+)`. This will match \"24M\" by capturing just the numeric part, ignoring the \"M\" unit.\n\nThe user's string contains several key details: apartment at 90 Washington, 24M rent, room 1, tenant named Zayan, spanning from 11/11/2026 to 12/12/2026, with contact information including email and phone number.\n\nI'm tracing the regex matching process, noting how different patterns extract specific information from the input string. The apartment extraction seems particularly interesting, capturing the full details before the room assignment.\n\nThe pattern matches complex location descriptors, pulling out precise location and room details from seemingly unstructured text. I'll continue examining the remaining matching strategies, focusing on capturing additional key information like email and contact details.\n\nThe regex patterns are strategically designed to extract specific data points through targeted matching, allowing for flexible parsing of lease-related information across different input formats.\n\nThe core issue emerges from the amount extraction logic, which fails to recognize \"24M\" as a valid monetary representation. By modifying the matching criteria to accommodate numeric values with optional suffixes, I can ensure more robust parsing of lease details. The goal is to create a regex that captures potential variations in rental pricing notation without overly rigid constraints.\n\nI'll investigate the existing codebase for alternative amount detection mechanisms that might provide more flexible matching strategies.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I see the issue — the regex pattern in the lease command expects \"amount\" or \"for\" before the rent amount, but your format has \"24M\" right after the apartment name. The current format expected is more like \"apartment X for $2400\" or \"amount $2400\".\n\nLet me check the Rent Tracker sheet to understand the current data format and manually update it:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0a93461336bf4f499ab64991","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd \"C:\\Users\\MudasserRasool\\.openclaw\\workspace\\skills\\google-sheets-api\"; node scripts/sheets-cli.js read 1RobrLNYSmMUyq53dUcdmj2ePaU2YkagqLqgIgx7M4OU \"R